Condition : 5 - Reserved Matters

For each phase (or part therein) of the development, details of the following matters (Reserved Matters) as relevant to that phase shall be submitted to the Local Planning Authority and no work except for demolition, site clearance and remediation shall start within the relevant phase (or part therein) until the Local Planning Authority has approved all of the reserved matters for that phase:

� Access (vehicular and pedestrian access within the site and to the building(s));
� Appearance;
� Landscaping and;
� Layout and scale.

Thereafter the development hereby approved shall be carried out in accordance with the approved details.

Reason: The application is in outline only, and these details remain to be submitted and approved in accordance with the provisions of Section 92 of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990.

Condition : 16 - Construction Environmental Management Plan (CEMP)

No development shall take place in any given phase until a detailed Construction Environmental Management Plan (CEMP) has been submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority for that phase. The CEMP shall provide details of how demolition and construction works for that phase are to be undertaken and include:

� The identification of stages of works;

� Details of working hours, which unless otherwise agreed with the Local Planning Authority shall be limited to 08.00 to 18.00 Monday to Friday and 08.00 to 13.00 on Saturdays);

� Procedures for maintaining good public relations including complaint management, public consultation and liaison;

� An Air Quality Dust Management Plan (AQDMP), incorporating an Air Quality Dust Risk Assessment (AQDRA) that considers nearby sensitive receptors, in line with the requirements of the GLA's supplementary planning guidance (SPG) 'Control of Dust and Emissions During Construction and Demolition' dated July 2014 along with monitoring of dust generating activities during demolition and construction.

� Mitigation measures as defined in BS 5228: Parts 1 and 2: 2009 Noise and Vibration Control on Construction and Open Sites shall be used to minimise noise disturbance construction works.

The development shall be implemented in accordance with the approved details and maintained throughout the demolition and construction phases of the development.

Reason: In order to safeguard the amenities of neighbours', adjoining businesses and the amenities of the locality.

Condition : 22 - Construction Logistics Plan (CLP)

Prior to above ground works in any given phase, a detailed Construction Logistics Plan, written in accordance with the latest TfL guidance or a subsequent version, related to that phase shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The Construction Logistics Plan shall include:

(a) A site plan (showing the elements set out below);

(b) Confirmation that a pre-start record of site conditions on the adjoining public highway will be undertaken with Hounslow Highways and a commitment to repair any damage caused;

(c) Provision for the parking of vehicles of site operatives and visitors;

(d) Provisions for loading, unloading and storage of plant and materials within the site;

(e) Details of access to the site, including means to control and manage access and egress of vehicles to and from the site for the duration of construction including phasing arrangements;

(f) Details of vehicle routeing from the site to the wider strategic road network;

(g) The erection and maintenance of security hoarding including decorative displays and facilities for public viewing, where appropriate;

(h) Provision of wheel washing facilities at the site exit and a commitment to sweep adjacent roads when required and at the request of the Council;

(i) A scheme for recycling/disposing of waste resulting from demolition and construction works;

(j) Measures to ensure the safety of all users of the public highway especially cyclists and pedestrians in the vicinity of the site and especially at the access;

(k) Commitment to liaise with other contractors in the vicinity of the site to maximise the potential for consolidation and to minimise traffic impacts;

(l) Avoidance of peak hours for deliveries and details of a booking system to avoid vehicles waiting on the access road;

(m)All necessary traffic orders and other permissions required to allow safe access to the site to be secured and impleme

Condition : 37 - Car Park Management Plan

No building hereby permitted shall be occupied in any given phase until, a Car Parking Management Plan has been submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority for that phase. The Plan shall include the following:

(i) Details of parking allocations for employees of the approved development and how this will be operated, enforced and reviewed;

(ii) Details of measures proposed to restrict parking to designated bays only and prohibit parking on the access road;

(iii) A commitment to install more blue badge bays and convert passive EV bays to active (as relevant) when demand requires;

(iv) Details of the operation of any gates or barriers.

The parking areas and access road(s) shall thereafter be managed in compliance with the approved Car Parking Management Plan, (or any variation approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority) and shall be maintained as such for the lifetime of the development.

Reason: In order to control the level and usage of parking on the site and to support sustainable transport objectives.

Condition : 40 - Circular Economy (audits)

No development shall take place at any given phase until, a detailed Circular Economy Statement in line with the GLA's Circular Economy Statement Guidance has been submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority for that given phase. The statement shall accompanied by the following supporting information:

� Pre-Redevelopment and Pre-Demolition Audits
� Site Waste / Resource Management Plan;
� Cut and fill calculations and/or Excavated - Materials Options Assessment;
� Circular Economy workshop/ meeting notes;
� Reused or recycled content calculations and;
� Scenario modelling demonstrating adaptability.

The development shall be carried out in accordance with the details so approved.

Reason: In the interests of sustainable waste management and in order to maximise the re-use of materials.

Condition : 60 - Fire Statement

Prior to above ground works in any given phase, a detailed Fire Statement shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority and by London Fire Brigade for that phase. The detailed Fire Statement shall include details of:

i) The building's construction: methods, products and materials used, including manufacturers' details;

ii) How the inclusion of the 'living wall' (green wall), (if proposed at reserved matters stage) will appropriately respond to fire safety requirements and be fire resistant;

iii) The means of escape for all building users: suitably designed stair cores, escape for building users who are disabled or require level access, and associated evacuation strategy approach;

iv) Features which reduce the risk to life: fire alarm systems, passive and active fire safety measures and associated management and maintenance plans;

v) Access for fire service personnel and equipment: how this will be achieved in an evacuation situation, water supplies, provision and positioning of equipment, firefighting lifts, stairs and lobbies, any fire suppression and smoke ventilation systems proposed, and the ongoing maintenance and monitoring of these;

vi) How provision will be made within the curtilage of the site to enable fire appliances to gain access to the building(s) and;

vii) How any potential future modifications to the building(s) will take into account and not compromise the base build fire safety/protection measures.

The development shall be implemented in accordance with the approved details (or any variation approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority).

Reason: To ensure that the development incorporates the necessary fire safety measures.
